The Macedonian people voted in a referendum on Sunday if they wished to change their name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece and block applications for admission to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim of its territory and has banned its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would harm the ethnic identity of the majority of Macedonia's Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether the result will reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum’s ballot was: “Do you support NATO and EU membership by accepting the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, allege that it is a price worth paying to gain admission to entities such as the EU or NATO of Macedonia, one of the emerging countries of the fall of Yugoslavia.
“Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us,” Olivera Georgijevska, 79, said in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, many members of parliament said they would abide by the outcome of the vote and would make it final.
The change of nine would require a two-thirds majority of parliament.
The state election commission stated that at 1 p.m. no irregularity was recorded.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent of the last 2016 parliamentary elections, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their votes.
