Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dushko tabled their vote for the Macedonian referendum on changing the name of the country that would pave the way for their accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the assembled tents for those who boycotted the referendum.
“We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads up and not through the service door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of EU and NATO membership," Zaev said after his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be “confirming our future.”
A poll published Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure that is below the required.
Another poll conducted by the Macedonian television network Telma indicated that 57 percent of the people surveyed planned to vote on Sunday.
