In Bolivia without sea, the memory of a lost coast to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict remains alive, as does the longing to sail back into the Pacific Ocean.
Those hopes are perhaps at their peak in decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision by the international court of justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the necessary momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, expects a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
