“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts consider it unlikely that the court would give a reason to Bolivia, and that little would change if that happened.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no power to assign Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the CIX ruling comes only six months after the final arguments we heard indicate that the case "was not complicated", says Chilean international law expert Paz Zárate.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years could have been delayed.
