North Korea Says No to Unilateral Disarmament
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions increased its distrust of the United States and that the country would not hand over its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important steps to show its goodwill" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test fields and committing to the proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see the corresponding response from the US,” he added.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disarmament on our part first.”
While Ri resumed North Korea's already well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as it had done with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean peninsula while Trump secured North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that first Pyongyang must lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive goal, and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to war,'" Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the American leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the other part of this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached a dead end."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after the “evil president” Trump called Kim “home rocket on a suicide mission.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for that, and that “it takes two years, three or five months anyway.”
China and Russia are discussing whether the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council: “Enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we observe full, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, just hours after North Korea denounced him for making "mafioso demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea vowed to dismantle a missile site, as well as a nuclear complex, if the United States adopted the "corresponding measures".
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he was asking for were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and progress toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
This year, a new course from Harvard University is making all of its students sleep longer in order to combat the growth of caffeine-stimulated sexist culture from studying all night long.
One academic has discovered that students at the world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact that lack of sleep had on learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why do you only tell me this now, in my senior year?’
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basics about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to present the course after discovering that students had a major lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficit affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed of how a lack of prolonged sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We don't know that the behavior of the students will change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in spending all night awake still exists, he says. And he adds that modern technology and the growing pressure for students that implied lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you get enough sleep and have good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he points out. Even avoiding getting fat, since lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which constantly makes it hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course throughout the campus.
The next step, wait, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm to lie down, as well as when they wake up. Likewise, it is recommended that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can unbalance the circadian rhythm and cause trouble sleeping.
