“What is this in the world?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you wear these headsets, you can hear the effects of atoms emitted by the radioactivity of the minerals.”
Evans: "Say, I'm sure it's popping right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name survives.
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” defective cells
