The San Jose cartel included 13 fights, with six being the main ones, and was broadcasting live in the UK on Channel 5.
But at 6 a.m., just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were going to see each other, viewers in the UK were puzzled when they saw the Peppa Pig appear.
Some were not impressed after spending so many hours waiting to see the fight.
One fan described the change to these children's cartoons on Twitter as "a joke of very bad taste".
“State law dictates that this content was not appropriate for 6 a.m., so it had to be switched to children’s programming,” said Dave Schwartz, Bellator’s senior vice president of marketing and communications, when asked about the broadcast.
"Peppa Pig, that's it."
Scott Coker, president of Bellator, said that they will take viewers from the UK into account in future programming.
“I think we can solve it when we think about repetition,” Coker said.
“But if it’s 6 a.m. there, we can’t fix it until Sunday, which is already Monday for them.
We are working to find a solution.
When the change occurred, I started getting a lot of messages and not all of them were nice.
We were trying to fix it because we thought it was a technical error.
But no, it was a government problem.
I promise it won't happen again.
We will limit ourselves to five fights, instead of six. We wanted to give the most to our fans, but we passed and
It hurts a lot.”
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality
Olympic jumper Tom Daley claims he grew up feeling inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but this made him find the motivation to succeed.
This 24-year-old athlete claims that he didn’t realize that everyone was like him until he got to high school.
Guest on the first broadcast of the Radio 4 program Desert Island Discs led by Lauren Laverne, he explained that he began to talk about the rights of homosexuals to give hope to others.
He also shared that being a father helped him to relativize the importance of winning the Olympic Games.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of this show, is on sick leave.
As a guest on Laverne's first show, Daley shared that he felt "inferior" to the rest of the people because "it was not socially acceptable that you liked the boys and girls."
“To this day, that feeling of inferiority and being different is what drove me and gave me the strength to succeed.”
I wanted to prove that I was “someone” so that people would not be disappointed in discovering their sexuality.
With two Olympic bronze medals, she became a prominent LGBT activist and used her appearance in the Commonwealth of Australia games to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He decided to talk because he felt fortunate to be able to live openly and without fear of repercussions, and wanted to give hope to others.
The three-time world champion said falling in love with U.S. director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "was a complete surprise."
Daley married this Oscar winner last year and claims that the 20 years of difference between them have never been a problem.
"When you live so long in such a short time" (at the age of 14 he first participated in an Olympic Games and his father died of cancer three years later), it's hard to find someone your age who had experienced similar highs and lows.
The couple had their first child in June, Robert Ray Black-Daley, and this birth caused Daley to completely change his perspective.
“If you asked me last year, my biggest motivation would be to win a gold medal,” he said.
“But now I know there are things that are far more important than an Olympic gold medal.
For me, my medal is Robbie.”
Her son is named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley’s father wouldn’t accept that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked his son for was tickets to London 2012, he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him I wouldn’t be here to occupy that front row,” Daley shared.
“I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and it was at that very moment, at the moment of his death, when I realized that he was really not invincible.”
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympic Games and won a bronze medal.
“At that moment I knew that that was the dream of my life: to jump in front of a crowd in my country participating in the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling,” he said.
The choice of Heather Small's song Proud is also not in vain, as it is the melody that accompanied him during his preparation for the Olympics and still puts his hair on tip.
Desert Island Discs on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
Mickelson in low form ended up on Ryder Cup bench on Saturday
Phil Mickelson will set a record Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup game, but he will need to improve his technique so that it does not turn into an unfortunate event.
Mickelson, who participates in the biennial event for the 12th time, stayed on the bench by decision of Captain Jim Furyk and was unable to participate in fourballs or foursomes on Saturday.
Instead of being the center of the action, like so many other times for the United States, the five-time champion spent the day cheering and working to improve his movements.
Although he was never the most accurate of players, not even at the peak of his career, at the age of 48 he does not fit on the tight Le Golf National course, where tall grass usually punish the wrong shots.
And in case that wasn’t enough, Mickelson faces off in Sunday’s ninth game to the precise Francesco Molinari, winner of the British Open, who joined Tommy Fleetwood to win all four games this week.
If the Americans, four points below starting the 12 individual games, start off on a good foot, Mickelson's performance could be totally crucial.
Furyk trusted his man, though he couldn't say much more.
“He perfectly understood the role he was playing today, he patted me on the shoulder, he passed my arm and he told me that tomorrow he would be ready,” Furyk shared.
“He was fully confident in himself.
He has a prominent place in the Hall of Fame and has contributed a lot to the teams in the past and this week.
I probably didn’t think he played two games.
I thought I’d play more, but in the end that’s what it is and we thought it should be.
Like everyone else, I want to be out there.”
On Sunday, Mickelson will surpass Nick Faldo's record in the most games played in the Ryder Cup.
It could mark the end of his Ryder Cup career, a career that never reached the level of his individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses, and seven half-timbers, though Furyk claims his presence also provides intangibles for the team.
“He’s a fun, sarcastic person, with genius and he likes to get involved with people, he’s a good guy to have on the team,” he explained.
“I like to see how good the youngest players have been with him this week.
He’s more of a good player.”
Europe captain Thomas Bjorn fears vanishing advantage
