Thomas is tasked with trying to lead the fight and take on Rory McIlroy in the first match, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the other Europeans, in the top half of the standings.
“I’ve decided on this order because I think it covers the whole way,” Bjorn explained about his selection for the individuals.
Germany's new warship once again postponed
The German Navy's newest frigate should have been delivered in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but it won't arrive until at least next year due to faulty systems and increasing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the leading ship of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, was postponed until the first half of 2019, a military spokesman told the newspaper Die Zeit.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but post-delivery issues affected the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships, commissioned by the Navy in 2007, will replace the former Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, with different anti-heretic and anti-ship missiles, as well as concealment technology such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, it should be possible to deploy the newer frigates up to two years outside the ports of origin.
However, as Die Zeit points out, these continual delays mean that warships with the latest technology, and that they will allow Germany to project its power abroad, will be outdated when they enter service.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind this return, but the German media spoke of "crucial software and hardware flaws" that made it impossible to use the warship on a combat mission.
The software defects were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors; that is, half of the necessary personnel on the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to have dramatic excess weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add improvements in the future.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to weigh twice as much as the ships of similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the total project price, which includes crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said that it already reaches the staggering amount of €3.1 billion, compared to the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems of the newer frigates are particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is taking water.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence committee of the German parliament, acknowledged that the Navy is running out of ships to deploy.
The officer claims that this problem is growing, as the old ships have been withdrawn, but not replaced by others.
He also regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates could join the Navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with manual detectors.
A sound analysis performed by experts of all recordings will determine the frequency of calls of bats and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape-scale image of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as prairie creation and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work that affects children and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightening also pose a risk, as do glue traps for flies, some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not blind.
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who carry out periodic surveys, inspections of children and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organization has even the first and only reserve of bats in Scotland at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland.
David Thompson, estate manager, states that this is the ideal territory for them.
“In Threave we have a large area for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there are many things we don’t yet know about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
It emphasizes the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the property, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity child can kill up to 400 females and offspring, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as destroy their children.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There's still a lot to learn about bats, and for many species, we don't know how it's doing to their populations."
