Brexit: Carmakers would leave the UK
The United Kingdom would forever regret losing its position as the world’s leading automaker after Brexit, according to Secretary of Commerce Greg Clark.
He added that it was worrying that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
“We need to reach an agreement,” Clark added.
The Japanese automaker said that if Brexit did not reach an agreement, the impact of delays at the border could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which is in charge of manufacturing Toyota’s Auris and Avensis models, produced about 150,000 vehicles last year, of which 90% were exported to the rest of the EU.
“In my opinion, if Britain leaves the EU by the end of March, we will be witnessing how production stops at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s general manager in Burnaston.
Other UK automakers have also expressed fears of leaving the EU without reaching an agreement on how cross-border trade works, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW confirmed that it would close its Mini plant in Oxford a month after Brexit.
One of the main concerns of automakers is the supply chain risk in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is very tight, every 37 minutes pieces arrive from UK and EU suppliers for custom-made cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without an agreement on 29 March, the border could be affected and delays and shortages of pieces could result.
The company says it would be impossible for Toyota to maintain a normal pace for more than a day at the Derbyshire plant, so production would have to stop.
Clark says Theresa May’s Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely calibrated to avoid such border checks.”
"It is essential to have a deal, and we want it to be the best deal, to enjoy the current success but also to make the most of this opportunity," he said on BBC Radio 4's Today program.
“Toyota and other manufacturers’ experience is that we need to continue these excellent supply chains.”
Toyota could not estimate how long production would stop, but warned that in the long run the added costs would reduce the plant's competition and could even cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, a 24-year Burnaston employee and Unite union coordinator, said its members are increasingly concerned: "From experience, I know that once these jobs disappear, they never return.
A government spokesman said they had presented a precise and credible plan for the future relationship between the UK and the EU.
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be postponed again.
The White House said the high-risk meeting of Donald Trump and Undersecretary of Justice Rosenstein could be delayed another week because of the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian interference in the election, ties between Russia’s aides and Trump, and the possible obstruction of justice by the president.
Whether Trump fires the deputy attorney general or not, which would jeopardize Mueller’s independence, has fueled rumors in Washington for months.
