A stamp tax will be applied to foreign buyers who buy property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher doorbell tax when they purchase a property in the UK. This additional money will be used to help homeless people under the new conservative plans.
This measure will neutralize the success of the Corbyn campaign to attract young voters
The stamp tax increase will apply to those people who do not pay tax in the UK.
The Treasury hopes to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help homeless people
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher doorbell tax when they purchase a property in the UK. Theresa May will announce that this additional money will be used to help homeless people.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign to lure young voters with promises to promote more affordable housing and focus on high-income people.
The stamp tax increase will apply to people and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK, and the money raised will be used to support the government’s campaign to reduce the number of people sleeping on the street.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp tax, including the highest levels introduced two years ago for second homes and purchases for rent, may be up to 3%.
The company expects the exchange to raise up to 120 million pounds a year.
Approximately 13% of new construction in London is bought by non-residents in the UK, which is driving up prices and making it harder for people who want to buy a home for the first time to have more difficulty accessing the real estate market.
Many wealthy areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost cities" due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson applied for a tax cut to help new people buy their first home.
He accused the big builders of keeping home prices high by buying land and not using it, and urged Mrs May to eliminate the percentages of tax revenue on moderately priced homes to fix the “shame of the housing sector” that lives in Britain.
Mr. Corbyn announced a number of attractive housing reform proposals, including controlling renters and banning foreclosures in which the tenant is not to blame.
He also wants to give the municipalities greater powers when it comes to building new homes.
“Last year I said I would dedicate my mandate to restoring the British dream: that life should be better for every new generation.
To do this, we need to fix the disastrous housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and start a life here.
However, it is not fair that it is as simple for those people who do not live in the UK, as well as for companies based abroad, to buy housing as it is for working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home is too far off, and the indignity of not having a roof remains too real.”
Jack Ross: “My last ambition is to be able to train Scotland”
Sunderland manager Jack Ross said his "last ambition" was to become Scotland's manager at some point.
The 42-year-old is enjoying the challenge of reviving the Northwestern club, which currently ranks third in League One, three points away from the head.
He arrived at the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
